{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_ginsberg_ver01/data/sn92066981/00517179668/1921020201/0848.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nLAEAMLE REPUBLICAN.\nPUBLISHED D tILY AND KE.MI-WEEKLY\nLnlerrd at the Ptmtoffk-v at Laramie.\nWy*. as mm-oiiil class mail matter.\nKEI\u2019I BLU.IN I*l BLISUING 0..\nrubliohrr*.\nr. S. President mid IMibic.\nTELEPHONE DI HEC TOK Y\nBusiness office 23\nity Editor 23\nS.-iety Editor 23\nTl KMS OF M BSCKIPTION\nPally, per week (I'3 carrier or muil)..lse\nDally per month\nDaily, three months fLUTi\nDally, six months\nDally, one year S7.SO\nSi-mi u Mkly, per motif II 25c\nbemi-weekly, three months 7Gc\nSemi-weekly six months $1.50\nHrini weekly.jyr annum (if paid In\n-'ll a n-\" I $2. .7.1\nMEMBER Of Till: ASSOCIATED PRESS.\nI he A\"-\"< fated Press Is excluslvp' en\ntitled to the use fur publication of all news\nlispati lies credited to It or not otherwise\nledited in tills paper and al.su the local\nnews published herein.\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nOne of the pleasant things of one\u2019s\nexperience is to follow the success ot\nthe men and women with whom one\nwent to school or college. When the\neditor of the Republican was in col\nlege in Hartford, Connecticut, some\ntwenty-live years ago one of Ins fellow\nstudents was a bright young New Eng\nlander by the mune of Weed. Charles\nFrederick were his Christian names,\nhut he was always called \"Freddie.\u201d\nThis same Freddie was always active\nly engaged in all departments of col\nlege lift*, but no one thought he was\ngoing to achieve a very conspicuous\nsuccess, but he has. He studied law,\nand has become not only one of the\nleading lawyers of Boston, but an out\nstanding figure in the banking and\ncommercial world. \u201cOne of the most\nimportant utterances of recent days\non the business outlook,\u201d says/ the\nSheridan Post, \"comes from Mr. C. F.\nWeed of the First. National Bank of\nBoston. It seems to us to be suHicient*\nly important to pass on for the benefit\nof the public, just as be spoke Jt to\na group of business men at a meeting\ncalled for the purpose of discussing\nplainly the affairs that were of the\nhighest importance to the men assem\nbled. Here are Mr. Weed's own words\nfor it:\u201d\n\"One rainy night last week an au\ntomobile turning too rapidly Into Com\nmonwealth avenue began to skid.\nWhen the wheels struck the curb it\ntoppled over. As the owner was emerg\ning from Its side a policeman came\nup and politely Inquired, \u2018Have an ac\ncident?\u2019 \u2018No. thank you,' said the own\nor. have just had one.\u2019\n\"I suppose that there is hardly a\nbusiness maj^ in Massachusetts to\nnight who does not feel that he has\nbad an accident, and it takes a good\ndeal of temerity on my part to stand\nup here and suggest that the average\nbusiness man really is more dazed\njih<|p .inured, that his machine is not\nbadly damaged, that the roads are\ndrying rapidly, that the danger of skid\nding is practically over, and that it\nhe wore planning to go anywhere it Is\ntune that he was getting under way.\n\"Nevertheless, that is how I feel\nabout tile present business situation,\nand these are my reasons.\n\u2018\u25a0There has been a great shrinkage\nin inventory values, hut what of it?\nDeflation was bound to conn*. We all\nknow it and we all freely predicted it.\nIt has conn*. perhaps, a little more\nsharply than any of us anticipated,\nbut, after all. may that not bo a bless\ning in disguise? There could be no\nsound resumption of business until\nthis inevitable deflation had taken\nplio i 1 It it had been spun over a per\niod of years a sound revival of indus-\nHr woud have been postponed just\nthat much longer. Ilas the bottom\nbeen reached? I do not know, but f\ndo believe that a basis has been\nrea< hed on which trading can be done.\nSoim things may go lower, put with\nmany staples below the cost of pro\nduction. ami below the cost of repro\nduction. with some as low as they\nhave been in fifty years, 11. requires\nno prophet to say that a business re\nvival is just around the corner.\nNow. in what condition does the\na\\<'ag>- business man find himself to\njoin in Ibis revival? IL is true that\nIns statement of this January will be'\nurn h b aner than his statement of\nla i January, but last January\nhi., statement was very fat. The real\ntest is, how does his condition now\ncompare wlllh his condition in the\nyears before the war? With few ex\n'pHons, notwithstanding the heavy\nfaxes that have been paid, the goner- 1\nous donations that have been made to,\n\u2022war charities, the heavy shrinkages\nthat have been recently written off, the\naverage business man today has more\ncapital than he had In 1913-14, and,\nif lie owns a manufacturing plant,\nthat is almost certain to be In far bet\nter shape than it was then.\n\"What the average business man\nneeds today, and all that he really\nneeds, is courage. If he will sit down\nand calmly analyze the situation with\ncourage he will cease brooding over\nhis own losses, and. what is more to\nthe point, he will cease talking about!\nhis neighbor's losses. Of these latter\nhe knows nothing, but misery loves\ncompany, and lie is willing to believe\nanything and everything and to pass\nit along The result is that the air is\nfilled with baseless rumors and busi\nness hesitates. You have all heard\nsome of these rumors and you each\nknow of at least one particularly ab\nsurd one by which you can judge the\nabsurdity of others. But do not mis\nunderstand me. I am not saying that\nthere will not be more failures. There\nwill be. I'p to date the business mor\ntality has been relatively slight for\nso great a slump. But the failures\nthat are coming have been marked\nfor a long time and discounted, and\nneed cause no general uneasiness.\nThe rank and file of New England bus-\ninoss is far better off than it was tn\n1914. Given courage it can go for\nward with confidence into a long per\niod of normal prosperity. There will\nbe no more vast profits. There must\ncome an end to extravagance and\nwaste. Competition will be taken.\nThe almost lost art of salesmanship\nwill have to be recovered. The levels\nof everything will bu higher than pre\nwar levels, but they will be as stable,\nwhen found, as were the pre-war lev\nels.\n\"1 have spoken of the necessity of\nbusiness men to cease rumor monger\ning.\n\"The public, likewise should dis\nabuse its mind of the erroneous idea\nthat business men are all profiteers.\nTlilnk for a moment of the absurdity\nof the popular contention that retail\ners must mark down their merchan\ndise bought at high prices during the\nwar. Why, bless your heart, these i\ngoods wore all sold long ago. Our\nbig department stores average to turn\ntheir stock over six times a year. That\nmeans, theoretically, that at the end\nof every sixty days their shelves have\nbeen completely cleaned ot every\nthing on them sixty days previous.\nTheir buyers are in the market ah\nthe while picking up merchandise at\nthe lowest price obtainable. This\nmerchandise goes into stock not to be\nheld, but to be sold and competition\nkeeps the prices down to a reasonable\nprofit.\nAnd, lastly. In this new era that is\nbefore us\u2014l think we should call it a\nhealthy era. Business no longer is\nsick. It was during the bloated years\nthat are over that business was sick.\nIn this healthy era the sanctity of a\ncontract must be universally recog\nnized. When a seller agrees to deliv\ner goods upon certain terms he must\ndeliver or pay damages. And when\na buyer buys he must take and pay\nfor the goods he buys. We have heard\na lot about cancellations. That is al\ntogether too respectable a term to ap\nply. Why not call them what they\nare, repudiations, and let the oppro\nbrium fall where it belongs?\u201d\nTO MAKE OPERA FANS.\nThe conquest of the East by the\nWest is always interesting. Generally\nsuch victories are (Hong the line of\nphysical or commercial achievement.\nBut in cultural matters, too, the inen\nand women of the West are scoring\nover the inhabitants East of the Ap\npalachians. This time it is the Chicago\nOpera. Under the leadership of Mary\nGarden that organization has invaded\nthe metropolis and all New York Is\ntalking about the magnificence of the\nperformances which It gives, and com\nparing them with their local metro\npolitan opera, and very largely to the\ndiscredit of that institution. Eveu\ngrand opera cun be benefited by ^o<J\nern methods, and Miss Garden has\nfound this out and has been applying\nthe remedy. One of the first things\nshe did was to hire an American\nbusiness man as manager, one George\nMiller Spangler, and he has already\nstartl'd in to change things. He tays\n\"that the average Intelligent Chicago\nman looks upon going to grand opera\nwith the same nervous hesitancy that\nhe exercises in accepting a position\nas honorary pall bearer at a public\nfuneral. The result is that he does\nnot support opera. He keeps away\nthrough fear, nothing else. 1 have\nfound a rather disparaging attitude\ntoward opera among the business\nmen. They go occasionally because\ntheir wives insist upon it. but they\ndislike the stiff clothes and the cere\nmonial and all the preparations.\n\"Now this attitude is going to be\nremedied If the men don\u2019t want to\nwear their 'soup and fish,\u2019 why, they\ndon't have to. It's their support, not\ntheir dress suits we want. Even if\nthey wear overalls they're welcome.\n\u201cWe Intend to make opera as popu\nlar us baseball. We want the business\nmon to be opera fans and to regard\nopera not only as a great Ihifig for\nthe city, but as a bully good enter\ntainment. We have been taking opera\ntoo seriously\u2014us something for the\nclasses instead of the masses. In an\nother year men will be going to the\nopera not to please their wives, but\nbecause they like it.\u201d\nROOSEVELT, THE BEACON LIGHT\nING NATION TO TRUTH.\nin a recent address before the \"Wo\nmen's Roosevelt Memorial Associa\ntion\u201d Mr. Coolidge has been saying\nsome very interesting things about\nTheodore Roosevelt. Mr. Coolidge be\ngun his remarks by saying that \"greut\nmen are the ambassadors of Provi\ndence sent to reveal their fellowmen\ntheir unknown selves.\u201d\n\u201cThere is something about them\nbetter thau anything they do or say,\nhe said. \"If measured at all they are\nbe measured in the responsive ac\ntion of what others do or say. They\ncome and go, in part a mystery, in\npart the simples of all experience, the\ncompelling influence of the truth.\nThey leave no successor. The heritage\nof greatness descends to the people.\u201d\nBut Mr. Coolidge thinks that it was\nnot in time of military peril, but of\ncivil peril, that the former president\nperformed his most valuable services\nfor America.\n\"The greatest peril to our institu\ntions.\u201d he added, \"does not lie in a\ndirect assault upon them, nor will it\ncome from those who, with evil intent,\nstrive for their destruction. Disaster\nwill come from those who probably,\nwith good intentions, seek the pri\nvate control of public action. It is an\nold story, known to all. in the ex\nercise of that eternal vigilance which\nthey tell us is the price of liberty it\nrequires constant reiteration and no\nestimate of the services and character!\nTHE LARAMIE REPUBLICAN\u2014SEMI-WEEKLY EDITION.\nof Theodore Roosevelt can be rfade\nwithout the retelling of it.\u201d\nAlluding to the derision some men\ncast at Roosevelt that he had \"discov\nered the ten commandments,'\u2019 Mr.\nCoolidge said:\n\"What they said derisively let us\nstate seriously. He bpd discovered\nthe \u2019ten commandments,\u2019 and he ap\nplied their doctrine with greet vigor\nin places that had assumed they had\nthe power to discard the ten com\nmandments.\u201d\nRoosevelt\u2019s last great service, he de\nclared, was rousing the nation to the\nmeaning and menace of the war to\nAmerica.\n\"He appealed from the things that\nseemed to be to the soul qf the things\nthat are.\u201d he continued. \u201cHe roused\nthe national conscience into righteous\naction. He spoke to the sou] of his\ncountry, and he saw her response. He\nsaw her rise triumphant above every\nsoridid motive, resurgent to the ever\nlasting realities.\n\u201cHe saw his fellow countrymen\nmake their sacrifices, and he made his.\nHe knew their suffering, but he knew\ntheir courage. He saw their final vic\ntory. He saw the beginning of the re\nturn of those never conquered ban\nners as they came streaming home.\n\"In that triumphant sound of drum\nbeat and bugle, he, too, was summoned\nhome, under the brighter banners of\nU'othj and righteousness, which, in\nhim, never suffered defeat.\u201d\nTHE ALBANY COUNTY TAX LEVY.\nIn his message Governor Carey took\noccasion to call attention to the fact\nthat there were great differences in\nthe tax levies of some of the counties.\nBy way of illustration he compared\nthe rates of I^aramie county and Al\nbany county, commending the former\nfor the fact that their levy was only.\n1.25 mills, and then went on to add\nthat the levy of Albany County was\n3.65. Un the face of it such a discrep\nancy would seem to call for an ex\nplanation, and it has just been forth\ncoming, but not in such a manner as\none would infer from reading the\ngovernor\u2019s message. On the front page\nof Saturday evening's Wyoming Tri\nbune a long article headed \"Low Tax\nRate Falls To Replenish County.\nFunds\u201d goes on to show that the low 1\ntax rate of 1.25 mills fixed by the\nformer board of county commissioners\njust before the completion of their\nterm in ottice, has placed Laramie\nCounty in an embarrassing financial\ncondition. Mrs. Ida R. Graham, the\ncounty clerk produces the figures to\nshow that the county will have only\nabout $54,000.00 available with which\nto pay an expense of approximately\nI $150,000.00 Their levy therefore\nshould have been at least as large\nas that of Albany county if not larg\n<br. In other words Albany county lias\nnot made a bad showing, but had\nbeen compared with a county wV* ci>\nhad failed to provide -the necessary\nrevenue, a comparison on the face ol\nit that was neither fair nor to the\npoint, in the figures just published\nby the State Examiner relative to\ncounty expense, there are eight coun\nties that have exceeded Albany coun\nty in its expenditures, and based on\nsuch a comparison the county has\nmade a very creditable showing.\nIT\u2019S BAD STUFF.\nLay off the home brew. It Is m\nonly dangerous, but is detrimental i\nhealth. Physicians over the couiirj\nfind an epidemic of gastritis ana\ntheir alarm has been brought to ma\nattention of health and revenue\npartments. The imperfect fermenta\ntion of ingredients used is the ri...\ncause, so the doctors declare. Those\nwho make their own, as a rule, cannu.\nwait for the completion of the natural\nprocess and the result is ordinarily\na nasty and unwholesome mess that\nhas a deleterious effect upon the\nstomach and digestive organs, dis\norganizes the entire system and ren\nders tho ordinary person wild.\nThe substitution ot home brew for\nregular beer for tonic purposes may\nbe set down as not good for what ails\nyou and you should cut it out unless\nyou want to spend your remaining\ndays in a hospital for incurables or a\nnut factory.\nThe appeal of certain medical men\nthat the manufacture of beer be per\nmitted for use for medical purposes\non physicians' prescriptions, has re\nceived attention, but no encourage\nment. There is no power except\nthe vote of the people that can re\npeal or amend the eighteenth amend\nment. mid no power except congress\nthat can alter the Volstead act. These\nare the laws of the land. Obey them\nand quit trifling with home brew.\u2014\nCasper Tribune.\nTHE AGRICULTURAL COLLEGE.\nThe bill introduced into the lower\nhouse of the legislature to separate\nthe Agricultural College from the\nUniversity of Wyoming would not be\nworth noticing, except that there still\nseem to be people who do not under*\nstand that this question was settled\na few years ago once and for all. it\nhad to be taken to the supreme court\nof the United States, bqt there it\nwent, and that tribunal decided that\nthe Agricultural College of the Uni\nversity of Wyoming was located at\nl^rsmie, and could not be placed\nelsewhere. Of course it is within the\npower of the legislature to establish\nanother college of agriculture, and\nlocate it in some other place, but\nsuch a college would not be the Ag\nricultural College of the University ot\nWyoming. That college is an integral\npart of the State University, and is\nlocated here at I^aramie.\nThen, too, there is a small group\nwho think that an agricultural college\ncan not be run on these plains, be\ncause of the altitude. Such is not.(he\ncase. The agricultural experts who\nknow say that an agricultural college\ncan be operated just as well at4-ara\nmie as anywhere else. One of the\nchief functions of an agricultural col\nlege is, of course, to train men along\nagricultural lines, yet in an institu\ntion such as the University of Wyo\nming, these men have broader oppor\ntunities and better facilities than they\never would have in an agricultural\ncollege that is a separate and distinct\nunit. All the departments and courses\nof the University are open to them\nand they can elect a range and vart\ntty of work never found in purely ag\nricultural schools. It is true that\ncertain experiments cannot be Carried\non here, that a few things cannot be\ngrown here, but to meet this exigency\nthe state provided a number of farms\nsituated in different sections of the\nstate, and on these farms such experi\nments can be carried on, and all the\nproblems peculiar to those sections\nhandled.\nIt should further be borne in mind\nthat Wyoming is a great stock slate\nand that stock raising is as much a\npart of our agriculture as crop raising,\nand that right here on our plains are\nto be found the conditions which are\ntypical of a very large section ot the\nstate.\nIn this connection one mor? point\nshould be emphasized. The strength\nof Wyoming's higher educational\nscheme lies in its unity. Here at 1-ara\nmie are united all the Institutions,\nwhich In Colorado are divided into\nfive different ones, in Wyoming one\nboard, one president, one faculty and\none grout of buildings serve the peo\nple of the state in its higher educa\ntion. In Colorado it takes five boards,\nfive presidents, fIVe faculties and five\ngroups of buildings to do the same\njob. For presidents alone our neigh\nboring state pays out over |30,00(H)0.\nas compared with our $5,000.00. The\namount of reduplication, the waste\nand the lack of efficiency is enormous.\nIf any dispassionate person will con\nsuit the authorities in states with\ndivided institutions he will find sucl!\nauthorities unanimous in their opin\nion that the Wyoming plan is the best.\nMany of the older states would adopt\nIt even now. except that because of\ntradition and sentiment the necessary\nchanges are almost Impossible.\nWherever the state universities are\nthe greatest this plan is followed, as\nInstance Wisconsin. Illinois. Miu ie\nsota and Nebraska. Let Wyoming re\nfuse to change a policy which is, i ot\nonly in line with the best educational\npractice, but also sensible, economical\nefficient and, successful.\nFOREST OFFICE NOTES.\nActing Supervisor Coughlin, who\nmade an auto trip to the Rex Lake\noil field on an inspection tour yes-!\nterday, reports that there is very j\nlittle snow west of Plains station,:\nand the going is exceptionally good.\nWinter autoing is just as pleasurable\nas summer, and the local forest ot\u00df-i\nerrs are looking forward to the day\nwhen a nice highway will link up'\nLaramie with Centennial and we can\ngo out to winter sports carnivals, skll!\ncontests, toboggan sliding, and what\nnot, in the area between Centennial j\nand Snowy range. The site is there\nand handy to l>aramie, and there isj\nno apparent reason why we should j\nnot have some of these things as;\neasily, and maybe more so, as Steam\nboat Springs and such points. The 1\nLittle I^aramie river is open in places.'\nForest Raflger Chaifan Stoddard'\narrived from Gramm, partly by skh\nand partly by the Mike Burns stage\nservice, last Saturday evening.\nIt *.ngor Stoddard has been detailed to\na ton-days tour of duty In the Lara\nml? office, -assisting Mir. Coughlin,\nwho along with his many other ac\ncoinplishments is property custodian\nof tho .Medicine Bow forest, in making\na chec\u2019. of the government property\nand in i general re-organization of\nUio local ofllces and store room. Stod\ndard has had many years experience\nin this lino of work In the army, and\nin the customs service, including sev\neral years in the Philippines. Ono ot\nthe annual duties the forest ranger\nJust loves and adores is the annual\nproperty check. Mrs. Stoddard remain\ned at Gramm, as she has some chick\nens which cannot be left under the\ncare of anyone else.\nA forest officer noting the proposed\ncountry club, has suggested that Cen\ntennial should be the location, since\nat the expected rate of growth Fort\nSanders will In the course of a year\nor so be In the heart of the business\ndistrict. The present distance to Cen\ntennial can he cut to Joss than thirty\nmiles, and from an engineering stand\npoint the road Bite would be Ideal,\nsince it follows the old \"Ridge Road\"\nalong tho northern rim of the Big\nHollow to near Overland, where is\nswings over through Wind Mill Hol\nlow and follows the Millbrook grade\nto Hatton, whence it trends due west\nto Centennial. This route as far as\nsnow Is concerned may be traveled\nalmost any time of year, and with a\nfew thousand dollars worth of con\nstruction \u201cCentennial In-Thirty Min\nutes\" would not be impossible.\nRECOVERED value of\nTHE MORTGAGED CAR\nR. L. Reece of Greeley, Colo., who\nwas here last week, looking for a\nman who had taken a mortgaged car\nfrom that city to another state, after\nward coming to Laramie, found his\nman Saturday afternoon, recovered the\nsum of the mortgage and permitted the\noffender to go without arrest, the mat\nter having been Axed up satisfactor\n\u2022ll'y. Mr. Reece returned to OrbeWy\nthat night. __\nTHORNS\u201c\u00bbROSES\nTWO SONNETS.\nJohn Masefield.\nLike bones the ruing of the cities\nstand.\nLike skeletons and skulls with riba\nand eyes\nStrewn in the saltness of the desert\nsand\nCarved with the unread record of\nkings\u2019 lies.\nOnce they were strong with soldiers,\nloud with voices,\nThe markets clattered us the carts\ndrove through,\nWhere now the Jackal In the moon re\njoices\nAnd the still asp draws death along\nthe dew.\nI'here at the gates the market men\npaid toll\nIn bronze and silver pennies long\nworn thin;\nWine was a silver penny for a bowl,\nWomen they had there, and the\nmoon and sin.\nAnd looking from bis tower the watch\nman saw\nGreen fields for miles, the roads, the\ngreat king\u2019s law.\n\nSo shall we be; so will our cities lie.\nUnknown beneath the grasses of the\nsummer,\nWalls without roofs, naves open to the\nsky,\nDoors open to the wind, the only\ncomer.\nAnd men will grub the ruin, eyes will\npeer,\nFingers will grope for pennies,\nbrains will tire\nTo chronicle the skills we practiced\nhere,\nWhile still we breathed the wind\nand trod the mire.\nO. like the ghost at dawn, scarad by\nthe cock,\nLet us make haste, to let the spirit,\ndive\nDeep in self's sea, until the deeps un\nlock\nThe depths and sunken gold of\ning alive.\nTill, though our Many pass, a Some\nthing stands\nAloft through Time that covers all\nwith sands.\n\n.John Burroughs publishes, as the\nfruit of his eighty years, a book of\nphilosophy called \"Accepting the Uni\nverse.\u2019\u2019 .John must have a stubborn\ndisposition, if it took him that4eng to\nfind out that there wasn't anything\nelse he could do about it.\nAnyway, a philosopher is merely a\nman who says \"I should worry\u201d and\ntakes four hundred pages and a dic\ntionary full of long words to say it.\n\nA Job for Adam.\nWe wonder If that expedition that\nis leaving for the interior of Asia in\nsearch of the missing link has con\nsidered the fact that If they find him\nthey will have to think up a new\nname for him.\n\nHeroic Methods.\nReginald once in a mood of choler\nThrust his head under a traction\nroller.\nThe neighbors were strangely sur\nprised to find\nHow the mishap had broadened Reg\ngie's mind.\n\u2014American Legion Weekly.\n\nThe Cheerful Idiot saw the headline\nlast night: \"Annual Dinner by Coun\nell of industry February 14.\" \"Gosh,\"\nhe chortled. \u201cI\u2019m glad I don't belong.\nI prefer mine oftoner than that!\u201d\n\nTho, mot tq \"Roost; Don't Knock.\u201d is\nvery popular. But 'just think what\nwould happen if someone applied It\nI literally to the door of your office!\nMany a single man has been kuowi\nto lead double life.\n\nOne can\u2019t help wondering whet he\nthe man who would reform the worl I\nhas succeeded In making one ma;\nperfect.\u2014Louisville Post.\nThe information that the Mar Betel\ngeuse is twenty-seven million times as\nlarge as our own sun should not be\ngiven too wide circulation. C'-tain\npeople we know are bound to become\ndecidedly irate because they have to\nbe satisfied with anything as second\nrate as our own luminary seems to be.\n\nPaean of Praiae.\nFor days my soul, o'erbowed with care,\nHas known po light, of Joy or mirth.\nNo sunbeam glimmering apy whore\nHas lit the somber, mournful earth.\nI walked my path as one bereft\nOf all that made my life worth\nwhile;\nIn all the world there was not left\nOne thing to conjure forth, a smile.\nBut now\u2019 I greet my friends with joy;\nI poutfd them blithely on the back;\nI bubble o\u2019er with mirth. Oh. boy.\nI'm glad that Father Jiggs is back!\nWe see that the silk shirt has de\nparted. Well, probably it's tetter off.\n\u2014Brooklyn Eagle.\n\nDon\u2019t be too hard on the doctors.\nIt Is true that they usher all the pests\ninto the World, but isn\u2019t it \u2019equally\ntrue that they help them on their\nway out\n\n\"What They Are Saying in Ireland\"\nis the title of a recent article in Vol-\nWednesday, February t, 1921.\niter\u2019s. For the sake of the feminine\nreaders of that great family magazine\nwe trust it is not a verbatim account.\nLOWBROW LYRICS.\nLooking Forward.\nThe silent woods are all drifted over.\nDrifted are the trails 1 used to know.\nAnd the river stretches white beneatn\na cover\nThat hints not of the singing stream\nbelow.\nThere is not a breath of life along the\nvalleys\nBut a lone w\u2019lnd walking, lost and\nhungering,\nAnd the snow-wreaths flit along the\nforest alleys,\nWhere the silent poplars sleep and\ndream of spring.\nBut at night time, when the storm\nwinds rage and bicker,\nAnd hurl their wrath against my\ncabin door.\nWhen on the hearth the embers fade\nand flicker.\nAnd the shadows dance a polka on\nthe floor,\nI like to start my old black pipe a\ngoing\u2014\nAs always Is the way with thinking\nmen\u2014\nAnd plan the time when ebiuook winds\nstart blowing.\nAnd the rainbows start to biting\nonce again!\nAnd I rustle out my fly-book and my\ntackle\nFrom their hiding-place upon the\nkitchen shelf;\nAnd I count \u2019em o'er \u2014the coachman\nand the hackle\nAnd the \"Killer\u201d 1 designed to suit\nmyself;\nHow this one snared that big three\npound Loch I^evin,\nAnd that the last big rainbow oi\nthe fall;\nAnd this\u2014the time I neared the ang\nler's heaven.\nWhen I hooked \u2014and lost \u2014the\ndaddy of them all!\nAnd once again I live those glad days\nover\u2014\nThose roving days of triumph and\ndelight;\nTill 1 quite forget the brooding winds\nthat hover\nAnd the moaning cold that crackles\nin the night.\nAnd I dream of song-mad waters,\nwhitely foaming,\nOf brown deep pools, where sulky\nbeauties lie,\nWhen lazy winds bring summer to\nWyoming,\nAnd the rainbow starts to rising\nto the fly.\nThe Retort Snappy.\n*\"I wouldn\u2019t be a fool If I were you!\"\n\"That\u2019s the only sensible thing\nyou've said during this discussion. If\nyou were I you certainly wouldn\u2019t be\na fool.\" \u2014Philadelphia Public ledger.\n\n\"Schwab Weeps on Stand,\u201d says a\nheadline in the Chicago Trib. We\nhope and trust that it was Valsparred.\n\nThe latest notes from the fashion\ncenters indicate it as quite probable\nthat ears will be worn again this\nspring.\n\nAnd while we'ro on the subject of\nstyles, how\u2019s this one:\n\"Mary, Mary, slightly airy,\nHow do the fashions go?\"\n\"Piled up hair and shoulders bare\nAnd vertebrae all in a row.\u201d\n\u2014The Puppet.\nWhy the War Was Won.\n\"The costumes of the ladles were\nexquisite, while the resplendent uni\nforms of the cadets lent a dazzling\ntouch to the conventional black and\nwhite of the masculine element.\u201d\u2014\nWyoming Student. Thus adding a\nnew chapter to world history, in dis\nclosing how the dazzling glitter of\nthose olive drab uniforms must have\ndazed and intimidated the Hun and\nthus made victory sure.\n\"Why, 1 knew her when her skirts\nwere down to her ankles,\" is now the\nproper form for denoting long ac\nqualntance with a lady.\u2014American\nLegion Weekly.\nLife\u2019s Little Irritations.\nAlthough I like to read the newest\nbooks.\nOne little thing my pampered spirit\ngrieves;\nJust where the hero braves the bale\nful crooks,\nI always have to pause and cut the\nleaves.\n\n\"I hear that Swift's house was en\ntered by a burglar last night.\u201d\n\"Yes, but by mistake he got into\nthe billiard room and got away with\nnothing of value.\"\n\"Ah, I see; missed his cue, as it\nwere.\"\nIn spite of Marion, Ohios\u2019 unprece\ndented demand for advice, there is no\nnoticeable shortage anywhere else.\u2014\nBrooklyn Eagle.\nIt logins to look as though Mr.\nHarding were going to build his cab\ninet without Wood.\n\nThe Latest Style.\nMy lady is both fair and sweet,\nBut all my love It squashes\nTo see her clumpipg down the \"treet\nWith flopping, huge goloshes!\n\nFrequent Reminders.\n\"You only kiss me now when you\nwant money.\u201d\n''Gracious. George. Isn\u2019t that often\nenough The Bulletin (Sydney\nThe strain on family devotion reach,\nes the breaking point when al] the\nrest of the family Is waiting for the\nlucky one to get done with the com\nic section of the Sunday paper.\n\nLa Bells Dams Sana Merci.\n(If Keats had written It with an eye\nto subsequent movie production.-\nI met a lady on the plains\u2014 jf\nBonanza Barney's only child. w\nShe aimed two bullets at my heait.\nBut both went wild.\nI roped her when she hit the trail.\nAnd though she scratched and\nfought and cried,\nI said, \"I sorter reckon now\nYou'll be my bride.\"\nI set her on my packing boss.\nI stopped her shrieks with kisses\nten, A\nAnd struck hot-footed for the church\nIn old Cheyenne.\nAnd as I Whispered of the time\nWhen she would be my lady wife.\nShe cut the thongs that bound her\nwrists\nShe used her knife.\nShe said, \u201cMe be your lady wife?\nWell. I guess not, you pie-face stiff!\u201d\nAnd then she threw me from the\nAnd off a cliff.\nAnd that is why I sojourn here,\nAlone and palely loitering\u2014\nBonanza's daughter was too rough\nFor me, by jing!\n\u2014James J. Montague in New York\nWorld.\n\nA lawyer is a lucky man. He is the\nonly person who has the fun of giv\ning advice, and gets paid for it be\nsides.\n\nA Good Crop.\n\"How much did your corn make\nthis year?\u2019\u2019\n\"About twenty gallons to the acre.\n\nJust after he\u2019s W a heated argu\nment with the clerk in the postoffice\nthe average man wonders just why\nthey call It the civil service.\n\n\"Society Matrons Aid Poor Artists\nDevelop Talents\u201d says a headline. As\nif there were not too many poor ar\ntists already.\nThough the bride may outwardw\naccede to the part of the marriage cer\nemony in which she accepts him for\nbetter or for worse, we wonder how\nmany of her would go ahead if she had\nthe remotest idea that there might be\nany of the latter.\n\nThe East may not be as woolly as\nthe West, but it\u2019s wilder.\u2014GreenvHie\nPiedmont.\n\nSince prohibition went into force,\nwe seem to have just about as many\nsorrows us ever, with no place to\ndrown them.\n\nLife\u2019s Little Irritations.\nWhat makes the mildest man say\n\"Damn!\"\nWhat turns his scalp-lock white?\n'Tis the half-shut door that starts to\nslam\nIn tho dark of a winter night\n\nOddly Quiet.\nThree hundred odd persons listened\nquietly during Dr. Craft\u2019s three-quar\nter-hour address.\u2014New York Times.\n\"Hus your new house all the modern\nconveniences?\"\n\"Oh. yes; concealed cupboard, pri\nvate still, everything.\u201d\n\nPaderewski announces that he wants\nto come to the United States for a\nrest. When he finds it we hope he\u2019B\ntell all of us where to look.\nTO ELECT, OFFICERS FOR\nCOUNTRY CLUB WEDNESDAY\nWith several yet to hear from to\nday this afternoon the list of those\nwho have signed as wanting to become\nmembers of tho proposed country\nclub had reached 97. It has been de\ncided to limit the membership to 125,\nand that leaves only a limited number\nof memberships available.\nA meeting .has been called tor\nWednesday evening, at the Council\nof Industry offices, when a permanent\norganization will be effected, witly\nelection of officers and board of direc\ntors. At the meeting held last week\na temporary board of directors yras\nselected, headed by Ross Moudy, and\nincluding W. E. Corthell, Mr. White,\nE. L. Woodford, Elmer Keefe, Stan\nley Edwards and G. U. Shoemaker.\nAll these men have been busy 'this\nweek and have Interviewed the pro\nspective members, securing nines\nwithout any difficulty whatever,\nThe plan ot having such,' %\u2018ch^b\nseems to be meeting With general ap\nproval. The old.officers\u2019 quarters at\nFort Sanders have been selected as\na tentative site, and cont^efort, have\nbeen making estimates thia week to\nsee how much it would cost to fit the\nplace up properly. The members ex\npect to have a place for tennis courts,\ngolf links, etc., and a nicely fitted\nclub house.\nAll those who have signed up on\nthe membership lists are urged to be'\npresent at the meeting Wednesday\nevening.\nCALLED TO DENVER\nWITH HER BROTHER\nMiss Esther O\u2019Donnell, clerk in Fred\nIhmsen's office at the court house,\nwent to Denver this morning. Join\ning her brother, Frank O\u2019Dounett of\nRawlins, on train No. 18, Mr. O\u2019Don\nnell going to that city for an opera\ntion for appendicitis. M","height":"20640","width":"15784"}}
